l natural $n$. Is this sequence monotone, antimonotone, converging? Prove your answer using any theory covered in the lectures.##Proof Using Cauchy Criterion#Conclusion":[500,509],"#10) Let $a_{0}=1,\\ a_{1}= 2$ and $a_{n+2} = \\frac{a_{n}+(M-1)\\times a_{n+1}}{M}$ for all natural $n$. Is this sequence monotone, antimonotone, converging? Prove your answer using any theory covered in the lectures.##Proof Using Cauchy Criterion#Conclusion#{1}":[502,509],"#11) An open set of reals is any set that contains a neighborhood of each of its points. A closed set is the set-theoretic complement in $\\mathbb{R}$ of an open set. Draw (sketch) on the real axis the following sets: a) $|x+M| <2$ b) $|2x-2|\\geq M$ c) $M-1 \\leq |x+M| < M$. Which of these sets are open, close or are neither open nor closes? Prove your answer.":[510,573],"#11) An open set of reals is any set that contains a neighborhood of each of its points. A closed set is the set-theoretic complement in $\\mathbb{R}$ of an open set. Draw (sketch) on the real axis the following sets: a) $|x+M| <2$ b) $|2x-2|\\geq M$ c) $M-1 \\leq |x+M| < M$. Which of these sets are open, close or are neither open nor closes? Prove your answer.#{1}":[511,511],"#11) An open set of reals is any set that contains a neighborhood of each of its points. A closed set is the set-theoretic complement in $\\mathbb{R}$ of an open set. Draw (sketch) on the real axis the following sets: a) $|x+M| <2$ b) $|2x-2|\\geq M$ c) $M-1 \\leq |x+M| < M$. Which of these sets are open, close or are neither open nor closes? Prove your answer.#{2}":[512,513],"#11) An open set of reals is any set that contains a neighborhood of each of its points. A closed set is the set-theoretic complement in $\\mathbb{R}$ of an open set. Draw (sketch) on the real axis the following sets: a) $|x+M| <2$ b) $|2x-2|\\geq M$ c) $M-1 \\leq |x+M| < M$. Which of these sets are open, close or are neither open nor closes? Prove your answer.#{3}":[514,522],"#11) An open set of reals i